Question 2
Grouping by two variables.
a. How many levels does var_2 have? How many levels does var_3have? How many possible combinations are there of the levels of var_2 and var_3? You should use code to support your answers to each component of this question.






Tip



Hint: The functions unique() and count() may be helpful here.


b. What does the following code chunk do? Run it and analyze the result and articulate in words what the pipeline does. Then, comment on what the message says.

df |&gt;
  group_by(var_2, var_3) |&gt;
  summarize(mean_var_1 = mean(var_1))

c. What does the following code chunk do? Run it and analyze the result and articulate in words what the pipeline does, especially mentioning what the .groups argument does. How is the output different from the one in part (b)?

df |&gt;
  group_by(var_2, var_3) |&gt;
  summarize(mean_var_1 = mean(var_1), .groups = "drop")

d. In the following code cell, we add one more step to the data pipelines from the previous two parts. The new step uses slice_head(n = 1), which is designed to give the first row of the output. Run the code cell and analyze the result for each pipeline. You will notice the results are different. Why?

# pipeline from part b + slice_head()
df |&gt;
  group_by(var_2, var_3) |&gt;
  summarize(mean_var_1 = mean(var_1)) |&gt;
  slice_head(n = 1)

# pipeline from part c + slice_head()
df |&gt;
  group_by(var_2, var_3) |&gt;
  summarize(mean_var_1 = mean(var_1), .groups = "drop") |&gt;
  slice_head(n = 1)

e. Run the following code cell and analyze the result. How many rows does the output have? How many columns does the output have? Is the output grouped? If so, how many groups does it have, and how many variables is it grouped on? Articulate the difference(s) between summarize() and mutate().






